definitions.definition: Hard, difficult; wearisome, tedious.
Strong, sturdy; great, massive.
Full; rich.
To rend (a solid material) by holding or restraining in two places and pulling apart, whether intentionally or not; to destroy or separate.
definitions.example: He tore his coat on the nail.

definitions.definition: To injure as if by pulling apart.
To destroy or reduce abstract unity or coherence, such as social, political or emotional.
definitions.example: He was torn by conflicting emotions.

definitions.definition: To make (an opening) with force or energy.
definitions.example: A piece of debris tore a tiny straight channel through the satellite.

definitions.definition: (often with off or out) To remove by tearing.
definitions.example: Tear the coupon out of the newspaper.

definitions.definition: (of structures, with down) To demolish
definitions.example: The slums were torn down to make way for the new development.

definitions.definition: To become torn, especially accidentally.
To move or act with great speed, energy, or violence.
definitions.example: He tore into the backlog of complaints.

definitions.definition: To smash or enter something with great force.
definitions.example: The chain shot tore into the approaching line of infantry.

definitions.definition: The surface described by the circumference of a circle revolving about a straight line in its own plane.
The solid enclosed by such a surface; an anchor ring.
A topological space which is a product of two circles.
definitions.example: A 4-variable Karnaugh map can be thought of, topologically, as being a torus.

definitions.definition: The standard representation of such a space in 3-dimensional Euclidean space: a shape consisting of a ring with a circular cross-section: the shape of an inner tube or hollow doughnut.
(in combination, n-torus, 4-torus, etc.) The product of the specified number of circles.
A molding which projects at the base of a column and above the plinth.
The end of the peduncle or flower stalk to which the floral parts (or in the Asteraceae, the florets of a flower head) are attached; receptacle, thalamus.
A rounded ridge, especially one on the occipital bone.
The dead grass that remains on mowing land in winter and spring.
